				\begin{document}$$\begin{aligned} \ln {\text{REC}}_{it} & = \beta_{0} + \beta_{1} \ln {\text{ROILP}}_{it} + \beta_{2} \ln {\text{ROILP}}_{it}^{2} + \beta_{3} \ln {\text{RGDP}}_{it} \\ & \quad + \beta_{4} \ln {\text{RGDP}}*\ln {\text{ROILP}}_{it} + \beta_{5} {\text{DEPEND}}_{it} \\ & \quad + \beta_{6} \ln {\text{CO}}_{2it} + \beta_{7} \ln {\text{TO}}_{it} + \varepsilon_{it} \\ \end{aligned}$$\end{document}lnRECit=β0+β1lnROILPit+β2lnROILPit2+β3lnRGDPit+β4lnRGDP∗lnROILPit+β5DEPENDit+β6lnCO2it+β7lnTOit+εitwhere the subscripts i and t, respectively, denote the individual cross-sectional units and the time period. βi (i = 1,…,7) are the elasticity parameters to be estimated while ε is the error-term. The variable REC is per capita consumption of RE, measured in terms of kilograms of oil equivalent. ROILP and ROILP2 stand for the real prices of crude oil and its squared term, respectively. The unit of measurement of real crude oil prices is in terms of US dollars per barrel in constant 2016 prices. It is worth noting that the statistical significance of the elasticity parameters attached to ROILP and ROILP2 would portray a nonlinear association between REC and real crude oil prices in the context of the selected South Asian nations.

For the robustness check of the REC-crude oil price nexus, model (1) is re-estimated using two alternate indicators of REC, namely the share of renewables in total final energy consumption figures and the share of renewable electricity in aggregate electricity output levels. The corresponding models can be specified as:2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
